						  Message:<br><textarea name="msg"  cols="50" rows="20">Blockades are the worst balancing issue with this game if it isnt fixed I cant justify continueing to play and if I quit most likly all of my friends who are all active players will quit as well. At this point I have goten 10 people to start playing. Yes I know beggers shouldn't be chosers, and I admit that I haven't been playing that long. However, free or not, am I wrong in thinking that you guys would like more people to play this game? A game that you have spent so much time on and probably have much pride in? Well if so, than this needs to be fixed or newbies simply aren't going to enjoy the game and ultimately quit (just as me and my friends are considering doing). Well, I would hate to just complain and not offer any solutions so heres a few ideas my friends and I have been throwing around that I don't think have been suggeted yet.

   1.  Simply make it so it takes longer for ships to return from a blockade.

   2.  Blockades last 12 hours; or when you call your ships back sort of like the way sending ships to your allys works.

   3.  Make an option that lets you choose whether or not your ships will defend against a blockade.

   4. A method a friend suggested that might be a better way to handle blockading that would more fit what blockading is...
When you send ships to blockade a planet, the production of that planet is reduced to 25%. It is similar to stationing ships to a planet in that they stay there until they are recalled (at which point it will take several turns for them to return.) 
The commanders will gain a significant amount of experience, but the person being blockaded and losing production would be the one to initiate any combat, the defending player attacking the blockade as one would seige a planet. Otherwise, no combat would take place.

I dont know if these would work or not but something needs to be done to solve this issue. 

Thanks for the time and consideration. 

Mahoo
Tormented one and speaker of the Umbra Crusaders</textarea><p></p>
